image.asymptote:
// 3-D interactive (WebGL) figure.
import three; size(8.5cm); currentprojection=orthographic(5,3,3);
triple O0=(0,0,0), A=(6,0,0), B=(0,6,0), C=(0,0,6);
pen face=rgb(0.5,0.7,0.95)+opacity(0.45);
draw(surface(O0--A--B--cycle), face);
draw(surface(O0--A--C--cycle), face);
draw(surface(O0--B--C--cycle), face);
draw(surface(A--B--C--cycle), rgb(0.95,0.7,0.5)+opacity(0.5));
draw(O0--A--B--cycle, black+0.5pt); draw(O0--C, black+0.5pt); draw(A--C, black+0.5pt); draw(B--C, black+0.5pt);
label("$(6,0,0)$", A, 2S); label("$(0,6,0)$", B, 2E); label("$(0,0,6)$", C, 2N);
draw(O0--(7.2,0,0),gray,Arrow3); draw(O0--(0,7.2,0),gray,Arrow3); draw(O0--(0,0,7.2),gray,Arrow3);
label("$x$",(7.2,0,0),S); label("$y$",(0,7.2,0),E); label("$z$",(0,0,7.2),W);

statement.p:
A solid E is called z-simple if it can be written as
\boxed{E=\left\{(x,y,z):(x,y)\in D,\ g_1(x,y)\le z\le g_2(x,y)\right\}.}
Here D is the shadow of E on the xy-plane.

The correct integral is a sum:
\boxed{\iiint_E f\,dV = \int_0^1\int_0^1\int_0^1 f\,dz\,dy\,dx + \int_0^1\int_0^1\int_2^3 f\,dz\,dy\,dx.}
If one slice breaks into pieces, split the solid.

image.latex-image:
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.95, >=stealth]
    \draw[->] (-0.3,0) -- (4.5,0) node[right] {\(y\)};
    \draw[->] (0,-0.3) -- (0,4.5) node[above] {\(z\)};

    \draw[fill=purple!12, draw=purple!60!black, thick]
        (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (0,4) -- cycle;

    \draw[thick] (4,0) -- (0,4);
    \node[above right] at (1.9,2.1) {\(y+z=6\)};

    \draw[very thick, blue!60!black] (1.5,0) -- (1.5,2.5);
    \node[blue!60!black, right] at (1.55,1.25) {\(0\le z\le 6-y\)};

    \node[below] at (4,0) {\(6\)};
    \node[left] at (0,4) {\(6\)};
    \node at (2,-0.85) {the \(yz\)-shadow for \(x\)-slices};
\end{tikzpicture}

statement.p:
The bounds describe the triangular slab 0\le z\le1,\qquad 0\le y\le x\le1. So we can write the same integral with y inside: I=\int_0^1\int_0^1\int_0^x e^{x^2}\,dy\,dz\,dx. Now the inner integral is easy because x is fixed: \int_0^x e^{x^2}\,dy=xe^{x^2}. Therefore
I \amp= \int_0^1\int_0^1 xe^{x^2}\,dz\,dx \amp= \int_0^1 xe^{x^2}\,dx \amp= \frac12(e-1).
So \boxed{I=\frac{e-1}{2}.}
